  "prompt": "How do I prove that ((sinA) ^2) +1/ (sinA) ^2) ((cosA) ^2) +1/ (cosA) ^2)) \u226525/4?",
  "response": "To prove the inequality \n\n\\[\n\\left(\\frac{(\\sin A)^2 + 1}{(\\sin A)^2}\\right)\\left(\\frac{(\\cos A)^2 + 1}{(\\cos A)^2}\\right) \\geq \\frac{25}{4},\n\\]\n\nwe'll first rewrite it in a manageable form and then attempt a suitable approach, such as algebraic manipulation and use of AM-GM inequality.\n\nFirst, let's rewrite the expression in terms of \\(x = (\\sin A)^2\\) and \\(y = (\\cos A)^2\\), knowing that \\(x + y = 1\\) because \\((\\sin A)^2 + (\\cos A)^2 = 1\\). The expression becomes:\n\n\\[\n\\left(\\frac{x + 1}{x}\\right)\\left(\\frac{y + 1}{y}\\right).\n\\]\n\nThis expression expands to:\n\n\\[\n\\left(\\frac{x + 1}{x}\\right)\\left(\\frac{y + 1}{y}\\right) = \\left(1 + \\frac{1}{x}\\right)\\left(1 + \\frac{1}{y}\\right).\n\\]\n\nExpanding, this gives:\n\n\\[\n1 + \\frac{1}{x} + \\frac{1}{y} + \\frac{1}{xy}.\n\\]\n\nOur goal is to show:\n\n\\[\n1 + \\frac{1}{x} + \\frac{1}{y} + \\frac{1}{xy} \\geq \\frac{25}{4}.\n\\]\n\nFrom the identity \\(x + y = 1\\) we have \\(xy \\leq \\frac{1}{4}\\) because for two non-negative numbers whose sum is 1, their product is maximized when they are equal, i.e., at \\(\\frac{1}{2}\\), giving the maximum \\(xy = \\frac{1}{4}\\).\n\nUsing AM-GM inequality on \\(\\frac{1}{x} + \\frac{1}{y}\\):\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{x} + \\frac{1}{y} \\geq \\frac{4}{x+y} = 4.\n\\]\n\nThus we have:\n\n\\[\n1 + \\frac{1}{x} + \\frac{1}{y} + \\frac{1}{xy} \\geq 1 + 4 + 4 + \\frac{1}{xy}.\n\\]\n\nSubstitute the minimum value of \\(\\frac{1}{xy}\\) using \\(xy \\leq \\frac{1}{4}\\):\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{xy} \\geq 4.\n\\]\n\nThus it follows:\n\n\\[\n1 + \\frac{1}{x} + \\frac{1}{y} + \\frac{1}{xy} \\geq 1 + 4 + 4 + 4 = 13.\n\\]\n\nIt seems overly cautious approach provides a number much larger than \\(\\frac{25}{4} = 6.25\\), confirming inequality. Therefore:\n\n\\[\n1 + \\frac{1}{x} + \\frac{1}{y} + \\frac{1}{xy} \\geq \\frac{25}{4},\n\\] \n\nproving the required inequality is correct.",
